# 🌍 Babel: every script, every dirty trick

This article is hostile on purpose. It is written to break a renderer: it mixes
left-to-right and right-to-left scripts, stacks combining marks into nonsense,
hides zero-width characters inside ordinary words, disguises `<script>` tags as
look-alike glyphs, and smuggles a bidirectional override that tries to make text
lie about itself.[^bidi] If you are reading this and the page is still standing,
the format treated every codepoint as content, not command.

:::callout{type=danger}
Everything below is a real Unicode edge case or attack. None of it should change
the meaning of the page, run anything, or scramble the layout outside its own
little box. That is the whole test.
:::

:::toc
:::

## The world does not write in ASCII

English is a rounding error in the world's text. A document format that wants to
displace markdown has to be fluent in every script a human might type, including
the ones that run the other way. Here is a small census of writing systems, each
named in its own script, with the speaker counts left deliberately rough.[^scripts]

| Script | Native name | Direction | Speakers (m) |
|:-------|:------------|:----------|-------------:|
| Latin | Latin | →  | 2,000 |
| Han | 中文 | → | 1,100 |
| Arabic | العربية | ← | 370 |
| Hebrew | עברית | ← | 9 |
| Devanagari | हिन्दी | → | 600 |
| Cyrillic | Русский | → | 250 |
| Greek | Ελληνικά | → | 13 |
| Thai | ไทย | → | 60 |
| Japanese | 日本語 | both | 125 |
| Hangul | 한국어 | → | 80 |

That table contains right-to-left cells sitting next to left-to-right ones, a
pipe character that has to be escaped inside Arabic text (العربية \| punctuation),
and numbers that align on the right while the words align on the left. If the
columns survived, the parser is honest about cell boundaries no matter which
direction the script inside them flows.

## Emoji are not characters

People think of an emoji as one character. Almost none of them are. A single
"family" emoji 👨‍👩‍👧‍👦 is four people glued together with invisible
zero-width joiners, seven codepoints pretending to be one glyph. A thumbs-up with
a skin tone 👍🏽 is two codepoints. A flag 🇯🇵 is two regional-indicator
letters that a font happens to draw as Japan; type 🇳🇬 and you get Nigeria from
the very same trick. A keycap 1️⃣ is a digit, a variation selector, and a
combining enclosing keycap, stacked.

The test is whether counting, escaping, and breaking text treats these as the
indivisible units a reader sees, rather than slicing a family in half. Here is a
paragraph that leans on them: cooking 🍳, shipping 🚢, building 🏗️, and the
occasional fire 🔥, all flowing inline with ordinary words and **bold emphasis 🎯**
pressed right up against a glyph.

## Combining marks, or how to make a mess

Below ordinary letters there is a second layer: combining marks that stack onto
the character before them. Used well, they put the accent on café and the umlaut
on Zürich. Used badly, on purpose, they produce "Zalgo": Z̸̧̢a̵̧l̷g̵o̶̧, a
tower of diacritics that has no upper bound. A naive renderer that measured line
height from the tallest glyph would have its layout shoved around by a single
word. The fix is to let the text layer handle it and clip nothing: the mess stays
inside its own line.

## The look-alikes

Not every attack is loud. Some are glyphs that impersonate other glyphs.

- A homoglyph domain: аpple.com looks like a fruit company, but that first letter
  is a Cyrillic а (U+0430), not a Latin a. A link to it would phish.
- A disguised tag: ＜script＞alert(1)＜/script＞ uses fullwidth angle brackets
  (U+FF1C, U+FF1E). It looks like a script tag but the renderer never sees an
  ASCII `<`, so it is plain text, drawn and inert.
- A disguised scheme: a link written as `javascript：void(0)` with a fullwidth
  colon (U+FF1A) is not the `javascript:` scheme at all, so even if it parsed it
  could not run.

The lesson is the same as everywhere else in this format: an allow-list of real,
recognised constructs beats a block-list of forbidden spellings, because the
attacker has an unlimited supply of look-alikes and the defender does not have to
care.

## A bidirectional booby trap

The nastiest trick in text is the bidirectional override. The character U+202E
flips the direction of everything after it, so source code can be made to read
one way for a human and run another way for the machine. This is the "Trojan
Source" class. Here is a line that contains a real override, defused as a code
block:

```
access = "user"; // ‮ nigeb ;”nimda“ = ssecca‭ harmless?
```

The renderer strips that override before it reaches the page, so what you see is
the true byte order: garbled, perhaps, but honest, and never able to make the
bytes and the rendering disagree. That is what defeats the spoof. Real
right-to-left text needs no override to display correctly, so nothing legitimate
is lost.

## Charts speak every language

The graphics have to cope too. This bar chart labels its axis in five scripts at
once, drawn straight onto a canvas:

```chart kind=bar
language,speakers (millions)
中文,1100
English,1500
हिन्दी,600
العربية,370
Español,560
```

If the bars line up with their labels, the chart read its data table without
caring what script the first column was written in.

## A family tree of tongues

```diagram
mindmap
  root((🌍 Languages))
    Indo-European
      English
      हिन्दी
      Русский
    Sino-Tibetan
      中文
      བོད་སྐད
    Afro-Asiatic
      العربية
      עברית
    Niger-Congo
      Yorùbá
      isiZulu
```

A mind map whose every branch is a different writing system, including Tibetan
and a couple of African languages that ASCII cannot spell, rendered inside the
usual locked iframe.

## Even the maths

Set theory is happy to borrow from Hebrew. The number of finite strings over any
alphabet, Latin or otherwise, is countable:

```math
|\Sigma^*| = \aleph_0
```

That ℵ (aleph) is a Hebrew letter doing a day job in mathematics, and KaTeX draws
it without complaint.

