## 日本語 の 見出し

A heading written in Japanese, with another in العربية and one in Ελληνικά below,
exists to prove the table of contents can link to an anchor that contains no ASCII
letter at all. Scroll up: those headings are in the contents list, and clicking
them jumps here.

### العربية

A right-to-left heading. Its anchor is built from the same letters you see.

### Ελληνικά

And a Greek one, because the alphabet that named the alphabet should get a section.

## The honest conclusion

- [x] Right-to-left scripts render and stay inside their cells
- [x] Emoji built from many codepoints survive as single glyphs
- [x] Look-alike tags and schemes are inert text, not markup
- [x] Bidirectional overrides are stripped, so they cannot reorder anything
- [ ] Every script has a font on every device (not our job, but a real limit)

> A format that only speaks English is a dialect, not a standard. The test of a
> universal document is not the language it was designed in; it is the language it
> was not.

If you reached the end without the page reversing itself, a dialog appearing, or
the layout collapsing under a pile of accents, then every trick above was handled
as what it really is: text.

[^bidi]: The bidirectional override is U+202E, RIGHT-TO-LEFT OVERRIDE. The
"Trojan Source" research (2021) showed it could hide malicious logic in plain
sight inside source code across most compilers and editors.
[^scripts]: Speaker counts are rounded and combine first and second language
speakers, which is why they are deliberately labelled rough; the point is the
scripts, not the statistics.
